<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-02-06T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-02-06T08:00:00-05:00" n="460" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d460">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">721.23/1022: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-02-06T14:00:00+01:00">February 6, 1933—2
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received February 6—1:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>94. Drummond tells me that his latest information is to the effect that
                            Peru has rejected the Brazilian proposals; that Brazilian mediation has
                            come to an end and that an armed clash seems likely between Peruvian and
                            Colombian forces on the latter’s territory. He adds that situation may
                            momentarily become serious and cooperation of great importance. He would
                            much appreciate any information you have tending to confirm or refute
                            these reports.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>